<div id="review_374778673" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/374778673" />
    <a title="Kylene" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4456697-kylene"><img alt="Kylene" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1517543669p2/4456697.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/374778673?book_show_action=true">Jul 22, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kylene" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kylene" href="/user/show/4456697-kylene">Kylene</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer374778673" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6349787272111833539">This book was great...I liked it better than the first. Maybe it&apos;s because I already knew all the characters so there wasn&apos;t much need for character development. Maybe it&apos;s because the author just jumped in and got on with the cliff-hanging storyline. Maybe it was because it took place during the bulk of WWII. Probably all of the above. I found the characters&apos; stories to be so fascinating...Wally&apos;s in particular as he was a POW of Japan in the Phillipines. The whole time I was reading I kept thi</span>
  <span id="freeText6349787272111833539" style="display:none">This book was great...I liked it better than the first. Maybe it's because I already knew all the characters so there wasn't much need for character development. Maybe it's because the author just jumped in and got on with the cliff-hanging storyline. Maybe it was because it took place during the bulk of WWII. Probably all of the above. I found the characters' stories to be so fascinating...Wally's in particular as he was a POW of Japan in the Phillipines. The whole time I was reading I kept thinking...WOW! Major kudos to the author for his extensive research. I even googled a few places and events and sure enough...all real. The only parts I found a bit tedious was when the author would talk about homelife in SLC for the rest of the family...I was wanting to skip ahead to get back to the chapters about Wally, Gene, Alex, Bobbi, and the Stoltz family. This was definitely a great book, one I would highly recommend for fans of historical lit, WWII, and/or LDS fiction. </span>
  <a data-text-id="6349787272111833539" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


